<div id="review_2009777293" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2009777293" />
    <a title="Elena C." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/68070948-elena-c"><img alt="Elena C." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1585853320p2/68070948.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2009777293?book_show_action=true">May 25, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elena C." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elena C." href="/user/show/68070948-elena-c">Elena C.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/8132890-on-the-edge">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/68070948-elena-c?shelf=romance">romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/68070948-elena-c?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/68070948-elena-c?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2009777293" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer640920642639738987"><b>
  <u>2nd read, Oct. 2017:</u>
</b> nope, still not liking this. But at least I soldiered on and got around reading it till the end. As a (low) fantasy, On The Edge is pretty great, imaginative and fun. As a romance, it&apos;s a cabinet of horrors of the most sexist tropes the genre has to offer. <br/><br/><b>
  <u> 1st read, May 2017: DNFed somewhere around 60%. Or something.</u>
</b><br/><br/>It breaks my tiny heart but I&apos;ll have to put this book aside. There&apos;s just so much nonsense I can take before my suspension of disbelief rebels and dema</span>
  <span id="freeText640920642639738987" style="display:none"><b>
  <u>2nd read, Oct. 2017:</u>
</b> nope, still not liking this. But at least I soldiered on and got around reading it till the end. As a (low) fantasy, On The Edge is pretty great, imaginative and fun. As a romance, it's a cabinet of horrors of the most sexist tropes the genre has to offer. <br><br><b>
  <u> 1st read, May 2017: DNFed somewhere around 60%. Or something.</u>
</b><br><br>It breaks my tiny heart but I'll have to put this book aside. There's just so much nonsense I can take before my suspension of disbelief rebels and demands that I give it a fuc*ing break. And it does have quite a high tolerance for absurdity, I'm telling you. <br><br>I started <b>On the Edge</b> on the assumption that <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/21748.Ilona_Andrews" title="Ilona Andrews" rel="nofollow noopener">Ilona Andrews</a>, the Magic Duo behind the <b>Kate Daniels series</b>, could do no wrong: some reviews (specifically, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/572982361?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">this</a> one) gave me pause but I charged forward anyway because - heh, Ilona Andrews! I kept on reading until the aforementioned process gave me the finger and abandoned me defenseless at this passage:<br><br><i>
  <b>"My mother's parents died in a house fire. [...] Their death broke my mother. She just kind of died right then, but her body kept on living. She started sleeping around and didn't stop. She'd have anybody who'd have her. Married, blind, crippled, crazy, she didn't care. She said it made her feel alive".</b>
</i><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1509373602ra/24313802.gif" width="" height="" alt="" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><i>See, Lucy's weirded out too. She's just too much of a lady to start screaming "WTF" at the top of her lungs, but that's surely what she's thinking</i>. I mean, it's true that the human mind is a terribly complicated mechanism and so many things can suddenly go awry and make it work funny. It's also true that I'm no mother myself and both my parents are still alive and kicking, so perhaps I can't understand what Rose's mother went through. But some of my dearest friends do have kids and I just can't picture any of them neglecting their own children to go on a wild sex spree with married, crippled strangers as a reaction to the death of their parents, however tragic that was. At any other time it's likely that a major eye-roll or two would have saved the day and my mood, but the description of the woman's downfall was one of too many strikes against this book. <br><br>Because I’m really so very tired of authors resorting to <b>cheap dramatics</b> to fatten their plot. And I expect much more from Ilona Andrews than this. The whole thing could have been so much simpler: attractive young man likes attractive young woman, attractive young woman likes him back - fantasy setting. Spice it up however you want, but it's basically what this is all about: the melodramatic nonsense adds nothing to the story.<br><br>Rose's situation is dire, all right: she's the head of her family, she has to take care of two adorable but problematic little brothers (Jack is a changeling whose attention span is that of the young lynx he turns into while Georgie is sharing his life force with a plethora of creatures he resurrected, including their Grandpa), she’s struggling financially and she made the mistake of attracting unwanted attention to herself when she revealed she’s magically powerful. <br><br>The addition of Declan as a threat to Rose's life, freedom and family is absolutely ridiculous: the angsty drama between them doesn't feel credible for a second. After all, she likes him as soon as she sees how very hot he is. And since he’s hot she also immediately feels a deep connection with him. The fact that he’s imposing on her in every possible way barely registers because with him around Rose loses brain cells at a frankly alarming rate: yes, she complains a bit about his assholish and patronizing ways, but she does so while peeking at his sculpted abs, so all is well. <br><br><b>Whatever, girl: if you’re happy, I’m happy</b>. I’ll just quietly close my Kindle cover on you. <br><br>I can’t believe Ilona Andrews wrote this overload of tired, lazy tropes: must have been their <b>evil doppelgänger</b>. I hope the Evil Andrews didn’t put their villainous doppelgänger hands on the <b>Hidden Legacy series</b> because that’s what I’m reading next. But now that I know they’re around, I'll keep my eyes open.</span>
  <a data-text-id="640920642639738987" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

